# 1. Reminders

## 1.1 Monte-Carlo Prediction

The Monte-Carlo (MC) prediction estimates the value of a state ( s ) as the average of observed returns over episodes:

[
V(s) = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} v(s_i)
]

where ( v(s_i) ) is the return observed for state ( s ) in episode ( i ):

[
v(s) = r_1 + \gamma r_2 + \gamma^2 r_3 + \cdots
]

---

## 1.2 Incremental Monte-Carlo

After each episode:

[
V(s) \leftarrow V(s) + \alpha \big( v(s) - V(s) \big)
]

---

## 1.3 TD Prediction

At each step ( \langle s, a, r, s' \rangle ):

[
V(s) \leftarrow V(s) + \alpha \big( r + \gamma V(s') - V(s) \big)
]

---

## 1.4 Q-learning

[
Q(s,a) \leftarrow (1-\alpha)Q(s,a) + \alpha \big( r + \gamma \max_{b} Q(s',b) \big)
]

Greedy policy:

[
\pi(s) = \arg\max_a Q(s,a)
]

---

## 1.5 Approximate Q-learning

Linear approximation:

[
Q_w(s,a) = \sum_{i=1}^n w_i f_i(s,a)
]

Update rule:

[
w_i \leftarrow w_i + \alpha \delta f_i(s,a)
]

where:

[
\delta = r + \gamma \max_b Q_w(s',b) - Q_w(s,a)
]

